For the preprocessing of our data, we separated our responses from our predictors and named them respectively. The presence of NAs was also checked for and none were found. For this study, coordinates/columns x and y were not used. It is also important to mention that because our data has a target variable that is binary, our approach is a logistic approach. In addition to a logistic approach, we chose three methods pertaining to bayesian statistics; LASSO, RIDGE and SSVS. The response variable chosen is pos, the presence (1) or absence (0) of malaria in a blood sample taken from the child and our predictors are age, netuse, treated, green and phc. We discuss these in greater detail in our presentation.

Our study contains the values for WAIC, DIC, AUC, and Bayes Factor. Our goal is to make improvements on the model and see how we can best explain our information and determine which model outperforms the rest in either category. These values will be addressed and compared with the new values we find.

It is important to note that all of the data is scaled to reduce bias and compare all models with accuracy.

Bayesian Logistic Regression

Bayesian logistic regression models the probability of a binary outcome \(y_i\) given predictors \(X_i\) using a logistic function: \[ P(y_i = 1 \mid X_i, \beta) = \frac{1}{1 + \exp(-X_i \beta)} \]

The posterior distribution of \(\beta\) is proportional to the likelihood and the prior: \[ p(\beta \mid y, X) \propto p(y \mid X, \beta) p(\beta) \]

Bayesian Ridge Logistic Regression

Bayesian Ridge logistic regression includes an L2 norm penalty on the regression coefficients: \[ p(\beta \mid \lambda) \propto \exp\left(-\frac{\lambda}{2} \sum_{j=1}^p \beta_j^2 \right) \]

Bayesian Lasso Logistic Regression

Bayesian Lasso logistic regression includes an L1 norm penalty on the regression coefficients: \[ p(\beta \mid \lambda) \propto \exp\left(-\lambda \sum_{j=1}^p |\beta_j| \right) \]

Bayesian SSVS Binary Logistic Regression

Bayesian Stochastic Search Variable Selection (SSVS) logistic regression uses spike-and-slab priors to perform variable selection: \[ \beta_j \sim \gamma_j \mathcal{N}(0, \tau_1^2) + (1 - \gamma_j) \mathcal{N}(0, \tau_0^2) \]

Polya-Gamma Data Augmentation

The Polya-Gamma data augmentation method for logistic regression replaces the binary response with a continuous latent variable to facilitate Gibbs sampling: \[ \omega_i \mid \beta, y \sim \text{PG}(1, X_i \beta) \] \[ z_i = \frac{y_i - 0.5}{\omega_i} \] \[ \beta \mid \omega, z, X \sim \mathcal{N}(m, V) \] where \(V = (X^T \Omega X + \Sigma^{-1})^{-1}\) and \(m = V X^T z\), with \(\Omega = \text{diag}(\omega_1, \omega_2, \ldots, \omega_n)\).

Bayesian SSVS Binary Logistic Regression

ssvs_binary <- function(data, y, x, inprob, runs, burn, progress) {
  x <- data[,x]
  y <- data[,y]

  # Scale inputs
  x <- scale(as.matrix(x))
  y <- as.matrix(y)

  # Make a column of 1s for the design matrix
  intercept <- rep(1, nrow(x))

  # Create design matrix that includes the column of 1s, and the predictors
  designMatrix <- as.matrix(cbind(intercept, x))

  # Save the prior value to use
  myPrior <- BoomSpikeSlab::LogitZellnerPrior(predictors = designMatrix,
                                              successes = y,
                                              trials = NULL,
                                              expected.model.size = (ncol(x)*inprob),
                                              prior.inclusion.probabilities = NULL)

  ## logit.spike()
  if (progress) {
    ping <- runs / 10
  } else {
    ping <- 0
  }
  bssResults <- BoomSpikeSlab::logit.spike(formula = as.matrix(y) ~ as.matrix(x),
                                           niter = runs,
                                           prior = myPrior,
                                           ping = ping)
  bssResults[["beta"]] <- as.data.frame(bssResults[["beta"]][-c(1:burn),-1])

  colnames(bssResults[["beta"]]) <- colnames(x)

  bssResults
}

Beginning with Bayesian SSVS, the variables runs and burn in were tuned from the initial 10000 and 1000 respectively. After several attempts increasing these values we noticed the metrics for our information had little to no change in the wrong direction. The use of 10000 iterations seemed too great of a number for a set with only 5 predictors being used and I believe this was making our model too computationaly intensive perhaps pushing our model farther than it needed to go. I believe decreasing our iterations to just the right amount could provide us with a lower WAIC & DIC and also increase our AUC providing more precise estimations for our traceplots and density plots as well. The values I decided to stick with were runs of 5000 and burn in 1000. I wanted to keep my measurements accurate but still allow for the provided functions and tests to iterate enough to fully understand the model, I worry, similarly, a very low iteration would hurt my overall model the same way but with too little information this time. My burn in stayed at 1000, I wanted to stick between 10% - 25% of a burn in as recommended and found that at 20% I got the most out of my information without cutting to many iterations off.

To select significant models, a condition was placed in the data. We select the values not including 0 and take these values to look for which of our predictors contain an inclusion probability greater than 0.5 or 50%. A posterior analysis is then put in place to interpret our informations inc_prob as well as the mean and intervals from the 5th and 95th percentile. We can see the predictors performing the best were age, netuse and green through their inc_prob as well as where they would range. age and green suggest a positive correlation on pos(1) while netuse suggests a negative correlation to pos(1). Our other predictors contain weak inclusion probabilities but also contain the most uncertainty. By looking at the intervals for these features, we can tell our information is likely to be very wide and it also does not suggest we have a postive or negative effect on our response. This is important because aside from the inclusion probabilities, the presence of intervals with the same sign are crucial to the significance of these variables moving forward. The prior used for this moodel is the Logit Zellner Prior. Our prior influences our posterior probability by providing us with the highest probability at .62150. Our highest probability was chosen with the inclusion of only age, netuse and green.

Traceplots were put in place for variables deemed significant and at 4000 iterations, convergence was tested. Our plot appear thick and centers around a constant mean.

The histograms for our significant betas show clear peaks at approximately 0.26, -0.3 and 0.30 respectively expressing the precision we need for a powerful model.

Bayesian Ridge Logistic Regression

bayesian_ridge_logistic <- function(y, X, iterations = 5000, burn_in = 1000) {
 
  n <- length(y)
  p <- ncol(X)
  beta <- matrix(0, nrow = iterations, ncol = p)
  sigma2 <- 1
  tau2 <- 1
  for (i in 2:iterations) {
    # Sample beta
    Sigma_beta <- solve(t(X) %*% X + diag(1/tau2, p, p))
    mu_beta <- Sigma_beta %*% t(X) %*% y
    beta[i, ] <- mvrnorm(1, mu = mu_beta, Sigma = Sigma_beta)
    # Sample sigma2
    sigma2 <- 1 / rgamma(1, shape = n/2, rate = sum((y - X %*% beta[i, ])^2)/2)
    # Sample tau2
    tau2 <- 1 / rgamma(1, shape = p/2, rate = sum(beta[i, ]^2)/2)
  }
  beta <- beta[-c(1:burn_in), ]
  return(beta)
}

Bayesian Lasso Logistic Regression

bayesian_lasso_logistic <- function(y, X, iterations = 5000, burn_in = 1000, lambda = 1) {
  n <- length(y)
  p <- ncol(X)
  beta <- matrix(0, nrow = iterations, ncol = p)
  tau <- rep(1, p)
  for (i in 2:iterations) {
    # Sample beta
    Sigma_beta <- solve(t(X) %*% X + diag(1/tau, p, p))
    mu_beta <- Sigma_beta %*% t(X) %*% y
    beta[i, ] <- mvrnorm(1, mu = mu_beta, Sigma = Sigma_beta)
    # Sample tau
    for (j in 1:p) {
      tau[j] <- 1 / rgamma(1, shape = 1 + lambda, rate = abs(beta[i, j]) + lambda)
    }
  }
  beta <- beta[-c(1:burn_in), ]
  return(beta)
}

# Example usage

5-Fold Cross-Validation and AUC Comparison

library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
set.seed(123)

# Prepare data for 5-fold cross-validation
folds <- createFolds(Y, k = 5, list = TRUE)

# Function to calculate AUC for model predictions
calculate_auc <- function(actual, predicted) {
  roc_curve <- roc(actual, predicted)
  auc <- auc(roc_curve)
  return(auc)
}

# Initialize vectors to store AUC values
auc_ssvs <- c()
auc_ridge <- c()
auc_lasso <- c()

# Cross-validation
for (fold in folds) {
  
  train_indices <- setdiff(seq_len(nrow(gambia)), fold)
  test_indices <- fold
  
  X_train <- X[train_indices, ]
  Y_train <- Y[train_indices]
  X_test <- X[test_indices, ]
  Y_test <- Y[test_indices]
  
  # SSVS model
  ssvs_model <- ssvs_binary(data = gambia[train_indices, ], y = "pos", x = c("age", "netuse", "treated", "green", "phc"), inprob = 0.5, runs = 5000, burn = 1000, progress = FALSE)
  ssvs_beta <- colMeans(ssvs_model$beta)
  ssvs_pred <- plogis(X_test %*% ssvs_beta)
  auc_ssvs <- c(auc_ssvs, calculate_auc(Y_test, ssvs_pred))
  
  # Bayesian Ridge model
  ridge_model <- bayesian_ridge_logistic(Y_train, X_train)
  ridge_beta <- colMeans(ridge_model)
  ridge_pred <- plogis(X_test %*% ridge_beta)
  auc_ridge <- c(auc_ridge, calculate_auc(Y_test, ridge_pred))
  
  # Bayesian Lasso model
  lasso_model <- bayesian_lasso_logistic(Y_train, X_train)
  lasso_beta <- colMeans(lasso_model)
  lasso_pred <- plogis(X_test %*% lasso_beta)
  auc_lasso <- c(auc_lasso, calculate_auc(Y_test, lasso_pred))
}

The dataset is divided into 5 equally sized folds where k = 5 folds are trained and tested. k-1 = 4 folds are used as training while the remaining fold is used as testing. This is done k = 5 times making sure every fold has been trained and tested.

DIC and WAIC

# Function to compute log likelihood
log_lik <- function(beta, X, y) {
  p <- plogis(X %*% beta)
  return(dbinom(y, size = 1, prob = p, log = TRUE))
}

# Function to compute DIC and WAIC
compute_dic_waic <- function(samples, X, y) {
  log_lik_values <- apply(samples, 1, function(beta) log_lik(beta, X, y))
  
  # Compute DIC
  pD <- mean(apply(log_lik_values, 2, var)) / 2
  DIC <- -2 * mean(apply(log_lik_values, 1, sum)) + 2 * pD
  
  # Compute WAIC
  waic_res <- waic(log_lik_values)
  
  list(DIC = DIC, WAIC = waic_res$waic)
}

# Compute DIC and WAIC for each model
dic_waic_ridge <- compute_dic_waic(ridge_results, X, Y)
## Warning: Accessing waic using '$' is deprecated and will be removed in a future

## instead.

Bayes Factor

# Function to compute Bayes Factor using Savage-Dickey density ratio method
compute_bayes_factor <- function(samples1, samples2) {
  posterior1 <- density(samples1)
  posterior2 <- density(samples2)
  
  prior1 <- dnorm(0, mean = mean(samples1), sd = sd(samples1))
  prior2 <- dnorm(0, mean = mean(samples2), sd = sd(samples2))
  
  posterior_density_ratio <- approxfun(posterior1)(0) / approxfun(posterior2)(0)
  prior_density_ratio <- prior1 / prior2
  
  bf <- posterior_density_ratio / prior_density_ratio
  bf
}

# Compute Bayes Factor for each pair of models
bayes_factor_ridge_lasso <- compute_bayes_factor(ridge_results[,1], lasso_results[,1])
bayes_factor_ridge_ssvs <- compute_bayes_factor(ridge_results[,1], ssvs_results$beta[,1])
bayes_factor_lasso_ssvs <- compute_bayes_factor(lasso_results[,1], ssvs_results$beta[,1])

cat("Bayes Factor (Ridge vs Lasso):", bayes_factor_ridge_lasso, "\n")
## Bayes Factor (Ridge vs Lasso): 1.007337
cat("Bayes Factor (Ridge vs SSVS):", bayes_factor_ridge_ssvs, "\n")
## Bayes Factor (Ridge vs SSVS): 0.0001698073
cat("Bayes Factor (Lasso vs SSVS):", bayes_factor_lasso_ssvs, "\n")
## Bayes Factor (Lasso vs SSVS): 0.0001685704

Fixing NA Errors in Bayes Factor Calculations

To address the NA errors in Bayes Factor calculations, we can implement a check to ensure that the densities are properly evaluated at zero. Heres the updated compute_bayes_factor function:

compute_bayes_factor <- function(samples1, samples2) {
  posterior1 <- density(samples1)
  posterior2 <- density(samples2)
  
  posterior_density1 <- approxfun(posterior1)(0)
  posterior_density2 <- approxfun(posterior2)(0)
  
  prior1 <- dnorm(0, mean = mean(samples1), sd = sd(samples1))
  prior2 <- dnorm(0, mean = mean(samples2), sd = sd(samples2))
  
  if (is.na(posterior_density1) || is.na(posterior_density2)) {
    return(Inf)
  }
  
  posterior_density_ratio <- posterior_density1 / posterior_density2
  prior_density_ratio <- prior1 / prior2
  
  bf <- posterior_density_ratio / prior_density_ratio
  bf
}

# Recompute Bayes Factor for each pair of models
bayes_factor_ridge_lasso <- compute_bayes_factor(ridge_results[,1], lasso_results[,1])
bayes_factor_ridge_ssvs <- compute_bayes_factor(ridge_results[,1], ssvs_results$beta[,1])
bayes_factor_lasso_ssvs <- compute_bayes_factor(lasso_results[,1], ssvs_results$beta[,1])

cat("Bayes Factor (Ridge vs Lasso):", bayes_factor_ridge_lasso, "\n")
## Bayes Factor (Ridge vs Lasso): 1.007337
cat("Bayes Factor (Ridge vs SSVS):", bayes_factor_ridge_ssvs, "\n")
## Bayes Factor (Ridge vs SSVS): 0.0001698073
cat("Bayes Factor (Lasso vs SSVS):", bayes_factor_lasso_ssvs, "\n")
## Bayes Factor (Lasso vs SSVS): 0.0001685704

Our Bayes factor for ridge vs ssvs is much closer to 0 at 0.0001698073 supporting ssvs over ridge

Our Bayes factor for lasso vs ssvs is much closer to 0 at 0.0001685704 supporting ssvs over lasso

A scatterplot was created using the x and y coordinates in the gambia dataset to see how the average presence of malaria or prevalance was seen in villages as we approach green-ness of vegitation

Some of the limitations that were introduced very early in this study involved tuning. Several attempts gave us slight changes but never in the right direction. It was only when iterations dropped that progress was finally made. The presence of as many as 10000 iterations likely caused overfitting and would not let our model accurately represent any of the information given. To overcome this as the increase of iterations caused worse results, smaller runs were used and caused our models dic and waic to decrease significantly; this appeared to alleviate the computational intensity the model mustve been going through to constantly iterate information. Another technique that was attempted but not used was the setting of an interaction term. The interaction between netuse and treated appeared to have some relevance when combined but this would have to wait for further testing as erros would not allow me to continue.

We used slightly different methods for determining if a covariate is significant; all 3 models each had their pros and cons.

Lasso does a great job indicating variables that are deemed insignificant and unlike ridge will remove variables as soon as a beta coefficient reaches 0. A con to this is given we only have 5 predictors, we have to be careful what variables we remove. The weight these variables have with less predictors can unintentionally have a negative impact on our results

Ridge is similar to lasso but does not allow our beta coefficients to reach 0 precisely. This can be beneficial to us in a model like this because we dont have too many predictors to begin with. A pro would be its ability to overcome issues like overfitting. Luckily for ridge we have a condition in place to remove variables for us other than the usual penalties. Both lasso and ridge are probably easier computationally but not as easy to interpret.

ssvs has the most unique and interprettable approach as it looks for inclusion probabilities for our reponse variable(pos) when there is a presence of malaria in blood samples of children. It looks for those with coefficients not equal to zero and intervals allowing us to see in which direction our predictors influence our response. A pro in ssvs is our ability to understand what our uncertainty looks like in the model and provide probabilistic estimates of important variables and relevant parameters. This is demonstrated nicely in the posterior probability and histogram above. A con of ssvs can be how computationally intensive it can be as well as determining which prior to use. We can evaluate these different priors in further studies.

Ultimately,

The Bayesian ridge logistic regression performs the best in terms of the 5-fold CV AUC, but the Bayesian ssvs is preferred by the Bayes Factor.

For DIC, Bayesian ssvs performed best and for WAIC Bayesian lasso logistic regression performed best

The Bayesian ridge logistic regression, Bayesian Lasso logistic regression and Bayesian SSVS all selected only 3 variables: age, netuse, and green.

One important thing to note is that of all the histograms, ssvs contained the highest range of beta coefficients. They suggested that age and green impacted the results of malaria positively and netuse impacted it negatively greater than any other model. Although the models themselves excelled in varying criteria, the impact ssvs suggests these predictors had on the pos can certainly be looked into for further analysis.
